# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: finops-practices
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:finops-practices/budget] A **budget** is a calculation plan, usually but not always financial, for a defined period, often one year or a month.
[src:finops-practices/budget] A budget may include anticipated sales volumes and revenues, resource quantities including time, costs and expenses, environmental impacts such as greenhouse gas emissions, other impacts, assets, liabilities and cash flows.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Companies, governments, families, and other organizations use budgets to express strategic plans of activities in measurable terms.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Preparing a budget allows companies, authorities, private entities or families to establish priorities and evaluate the achievement of their objectives.
[src:finops-practices/budget] To achieve these goals it may be necessary to incur a deficit (expenses exceed income) or, on the contrary, it may be possible to save, in which case the budget will present a surplus (income exceed expenses).
[src:finops-practices/budget] In the field of commerce, a budget is also a financial document or report that details the cost that a service will have if performed.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Whoever makes the budget must adhere to it and cannot change it if the client accepts the service.
[src:finops-practices/budget] A budget expresses intended expenditures along with proposals for how to meet them with resources.
[src:finops-practices/budget] A budget may express a surplus, providing resources for use at a future time, or a deficit in which expenditures exceed income or other resources.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The budget of a government is a summary or plan of the anticipated resources (often but not always from taxes) and expenditures of that government.
[src:finops-practices/budget] There are three types of government budgets: the operating or current budget, the capital or investment budget, and the cash or cash flow budget.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The federal budget is prepared by the Office of Management and Budget, and submitted to Congress for consideration.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Invariably, Congress makes many and substantial changes.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Nearly all American states are required to have balanced budgets, but the federal government is allowed to run deficits.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The budget is prepared by the Budget Division Department of Economic Affairs of the Ministry of Finance annually.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The Finance Minister is the head of the budget making committee.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The present Indian Finance minister is Nirmala Sitharaman.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The Budget includes supplementary excess grants and when a proclamation by the President as to failure of Constitutional machinery is in operation in relation to a State or a Union Territory, preparation of the Budget of such State.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The first budget of India was submitted on 18 February 1860 by James Wilson.
[src:finops-practices/budget] P C Mahalanobis is known as the father of Indian budget.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The Philippine budget is considered the most complicated in the world, incorporating multiple approaches in one single budget system: line-item (budget execution), performance (budget accountability), and zero-based budgeting.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The Department of Budget and Management (DBM) prepares the National Expenditure Program and forwards it to the Committee on Appropriations of the House of Representatives to come up with a General Appropriations Bill (GAB).
[src:finops-practices/budget] The GAB will go through budget deliberations and voting; the same process occurs when the GAB is transmitted to the Philippine Senate.
[src:finops-practices/budget] After both houses of Congress approves the GAB, the President signs the bill into a General Appropriations Act (GAA); also, the President may opt to veto the GAB and have it returned to the legislative branch or leave the bill unsigned for 30 days and lapse into law.
[src:finops-practices/budget] There are two types of budget bill veto: the line-item veto and the veto of the whole budget.
[src:finops-practices/budget] A personal budget or home budget is a finance plan that allocates future personal income towards expenses, savings and debt repayment.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Past spending and personal debt are considered when creating a personal budget.
[src:finops-practices/budget] There are several methods and tools available for creating, using, and adjusting a personal budget.
[src:finops-practices/budget] For example, jobs are an income source, while bills and rent payments are expenses.
[src:finops-practices/budget] A third category (other than income and expenses) may be assets (such as property, investments, or other savings or value) representing a potential reserve for funds in case of budget shortfalls.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The budget of a business, division, or corporation is a financial forecast for the near-term future, usually the next accounting period, aggregating the expected revenues and expenses of the various departments – operations, human resources, IT, etc.
[src:finops-practices/budget] It is thus a key element in integrated business planning, with measurable targets correspondingly devolved to departmental managers (and becoming KPIs); budgets may then also specify non-cash resources, such as staff or time.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The budgeting process requires considerable effort, often involving dozens of staff; final sign-off resides with both the financial director and operations director.
[src:finops-practices/budget] The responsibility usually sits within the company's financial management area in general, sometimes, specifically in "FP&A".
[src:finops-practices/budget] Professionals employed in this role are often designated "**Budget Analyst**", a specialized financial analyst function.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Organisations may produce functional budgets, relating to activities, and / or cash budgets, focused on receipts and payments.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Incremental budgeting starts with the budget from the previous period, while under zero-based budgeting activities/costs are included only if justified.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Under all approaches expected sales or revenue, is typically the starting point; this will be based on the business' planning for the period in question.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Directly related elements and costs are typically linked to these (activity based costing may be employed).
[src:finops-practices/budget] Support and management functions may be revisited, and the resultant "fixed" costs, such as rent and payroll, will be adjusted - at a minimum for inflation.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Capital expenditure, both new investments and maintenance, may be budgeted separately; debt servicing and repayments likewise.
[src:finops-practices/budget] See Financial forecast, Cash flow forecast, Financial modeling § Accounting.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Whereas the budget is typically compiled on an annual basis - although, e.g. in mining, this may be quarterly - the monitoring is ongoing, with financial and operational adjustments (or interventions) made as warranted; see Financial risk management § Corporate finance for further discussion.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Here, if the actual figures delivered come close to those budgeted, this suggests that managers understand their business and have been successful in delivering.
[src:finops-practices/budget] On the other hand, if the figures diverge this sends an "out of control" signal; additionally, the share price could suffer where these figures have been communicated to analysts.
[src:finops-practices/budget] Criticism is sometimes directed at the nature of budgeting, and its impact on the organization.
[src:finops-practices/budget] A second observation is that managers' thinking may emphasize short term, operational thinking at the expense of a long term and strategic perspective, particularly when bonus payments are linked to budget.
[src:finops-practices/budget] See Strategic planning § Strategic planning vs. financial planning.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] A **chargeback** is a return of money to a payer of a transaction, especially a credit card transaction.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The chargeback reverses a money transfer from the consumer's bank account, line of credit, or credit card.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The chargeback is ordered by the bank that issued the consumer's payment card, typically to settle a credit card dispute.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] In the distribution industry, a chargeback occurs when the supplier sells a product at a higher price to the distributor than the price they have set with the end user.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The distributor submits a chargeback to the supplier so they can recover the money lost in the transaction.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The chargeback mechanism exists primarily for consumer protection.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Holders of credit cards issued in the United States are afforded reversal rights by Regulation Z of the Truth in Lending Act.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] United States debit card holders are guaranteed reversal rights by Regulation E of the Electronic Fund Transfer Act.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Similar rights extend globally, pursuant to the rules established by the corresponding card association or bank network.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] A consumer may initiate a chargeback by contacting their issuing bank and filing a substantiated complaint regarding one or more debit items on their statement.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The threat of forced reversal of funds provides merchants with an incentive to provide quality products, helpful customer service, and timely refunds as appropriate.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Chargebacks provide a means for reversal of unauthorized transfers due to identity theft.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Chargebacks can also occur as a result of friendly fraud, where the transaction was authorized by the consumer but the consumer later attempts to fraudulently reverse the charges.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Card association chargeback rules are available online for public inspection and review.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] They comprise a system for adjudicating transaction disputes between cardholders and merchants, primarily where the issues can be resolved based on documentary evidence incident to the transaction.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The rules provide for arbitration of issues by the card association.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] This may occur where the card issuer generates a second (or "arbitration") chargeback against the merchant, after receiving the merchant's response to the initial chargeback.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Normally this would require the cardholder to rebut elements of the merchant's response.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The second chargeback results in a second crediting of the cardholder's account for the disputed funds, after having been credited back to the merchant with its response to the initial chargeback.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The merchant's only recourse after the second chargeback is to initiate arbitration of the dispute by the card association.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The fee for this is on the order of $250, and the arbitration loser is obligated to pay the costs of the arbitration.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] With each chargeback the issuer selects and submits a numeric reason code.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] This feedback may help the merchant and acquirer diagnose errors and improve customer satisfaction.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] One of the most common reasons for a chargeback is a fraudulent transaction.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] In this case, a credit card is used without the consent or proper authorization of the card holder.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] In some cases, a merchant is responsible for charges fraudulently imposed on a customer.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Fraudulent card transactions often originate with criminals who gain access to secure payment card data and set up schemes to exploit the data.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] In cases of card not present transactions the merchant is usually responsible for the chargeback and associated fees.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] After the adoption of EMV (cards with a chip in them), merchants who have not upgraded to EMV technology usually become liable for chargebacks received (unless others in the payment chain have also not upgraded) even in cases where prior to EMV adoption the merchant would not have been liable.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Chargebacks can result from not receiving credit for returned merchandise, not receiving items they have paid for, or if the items were not what they expected.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] In these examples, the merchant is responsible for issuing credit to its customer and would be subject to a chargeback.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Other reasons include charging the consumer twice for a single transaction or charging an account after the bank declined the transaction.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] For transactions where the original invoice was signed by the consumer, the merchant may dispute a chargeback with the assistance of the merchant's acquiring bank.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The acquirer and issuer mediate in the dispute process, following rules set forth by the corresponding bank network or card association.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] If the acquirer prevails in the dispute, the funds are returned to the acquirer, and then to the merchant.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Only 21% of chargebacks lodged globally are decided in favour of the merchant.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The 2014 Cybersource Fraud Benchmark Report found that only 60% of chargebacks are disputed by merchants, and that merchants have a success rate of about 41% with those they do re-present.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] To address these more effectively, technology companies have written code and built algorithms that help merchants determine if chargebacks are legitimate or fraudulent.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Reducing consumer chargebacks is crucial to this endeavor.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] To encourage compliance, acquirers may charge merchants a penalty for each chargeback received.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Payment service providers, such as PayPal, have a similar policy.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] PayPal Merchant charges $20 for each chargeback, when the transaction is not covered by seller protection (regardless of whether or not it is the first) plus it will retain the original transaction fee.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] In addition, Visa and MasterCard may levy severe penalties against acquiring banks that retain merchants with high chargeback frequency.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Acquirers typically pass such fines directly to the merchant.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Merchants whose ratios stray too far out of compliance may trigger card association fines of $100 or more per chargeback.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Merchant service providers may ultimately decline to provide an account for businesses with too high of a chargeback ratio.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Accounts may also incur credit reversals in other forms.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] ATM reversals occur when an ATM deposit envelope is found to have fewer funds than represented by the depositor.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] A chargeback is made to correct the error.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] This could result due to a counting error or intentional fraud by the account holder, or the envelope or its contents could have been lost or stolen.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Chargebacks also occur when a bank error credits an account with more funds than intended.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The bank makes a chargeback to correct the error.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] If an overdraft results and it cannot be covered in time, the bank could sue or press criminal charges.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] When a direct deposit is made to the wrong account holder or in a greater amount than intended a chargeback is made to correct the error.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Finally, chargebacks occur when an account holder deposits a check or money order and the deposited item is returned due to non-sufficient funds, a closed account, or being discovered to be counterfeit, stolen, altered, or forged.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Banks may sue account holders or press criminal charges when chargebacks are required due to fraudulent activity and insufficient funds are in the account to cover the chargebacks.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Merchants sometimes maintain a record of customers who chargeback regularly, in a "negative database".
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] A "negative database" in the context of merchants and payments refers to a list or database that contains information about customers who have a history of problematic behavior, such as frequent chargebacks, fraud, or payment disputes.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] Merchants use these databases to identify and potentially block or scrutinize transactions from high-risk customers.
[src:finops-practices/chargeback] The concept of the negative database was notably implemented by Jason Doongoos and Mario Rossi in the late 1990s, specifically in November 1997.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:finops-practices/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Often considered a subset or quantitative tool of managerial accounting, its end goal is to advise the management on how to optimize business practices and processes based on cost efficiency and capability.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Cost accounting provides the detailed cost information that management needs to control current operations and plan for the future.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Cost accounting information is also commonly used in financial accounting, but its primary function is for use by managers to facilitate their decision-making.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] All types of businesses, whether manufacturing, trading or producing services, require cost accounting to track their activities.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Cost accounting has long been used to help managers understand the costs of running a business.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Modern cost accounting originated during the Industrial Revolution when the complexities of running large scale businesses led to the development of systems for recording and tracking costs to help business owners and managers make decisions.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Various techniques used by cost accountants include standard costing and variance analysis, marginal costing and cost volume profit analysis, budgetary control, uniform costing, inter firm comparison, etc.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Evaluation of cost accounting is mainly due to the limitations of financial accounting.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Moreover, maintenance of cost records has been made compulsory in selected industries as notified by the government from time to time.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] In the early industrial age most of the costs incurred by a business were what modern accountants call "variable costs" because they varied directly with the amount of production.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Money was spent on labour, raw materials, the power to run a factory, etc., in direct proportion to production.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Managers could simply total the variable costs for a product and use this as a rough guide for decision-making processes.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Some costs tend to remain the same even during idle periods, unlike variable costs, which rise and fall with volume of work (and thus variable costs are higher in busy periods, and fall during idle periods).
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Over time, these "fixed costs" have become more important to managers.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Examples of fixed costs include the depreciation of plant and equipment, and the cost of departments such as maintenance, tooling, production control, purchasing, quality control, storage and handling, plant supervision and engineering.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] In the early nineteenth century, these costs were of little importance to most businesses.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] However, with the growth of railroads, steel and large scale manufacturing, by the late nineteenth century these costs were often more important than the variable cost of a product, and allocating them to a broad range of products led to bad decision making.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Managers must understand fixed costs in order to make decisions about products and pricing.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example: a company produces railway coaches and has only one product.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] To make each coach, the company needs to purchase $60 of raw materials and components and pay 6 labourers $40 each.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Therefore, the total variable cost for each coach was $300.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Knowing that making a coach requires spending $300, managers know they cannot sell below that price without losing money on each coach.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Any price above $300 would make a contribution to the fixed costs of the company.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] If the fixed costs are, say, $1000 per month for rent, insurance and owner's salary, the company could therefore sell 5 coaches per month for a total of $3000 (priced at $600 each), or 10 coaches for a total of $4500 (priced at $450 each), and make a profit of $500 in each case.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The materials directly contributed to a product and those easily identifiable in the finished product are called **direct materials**.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example, paper in books, wood in furniture, plastic in a water tank, and leather in shoes are direct materials.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Other, usually lower cost items or supporting material used in the production of in a finished product are called **indirect materials**.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example, lubricants used to keep machines running, or the chemicals used during the garment manufacturing processes.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Furthermore, these can be categorized into three different types of inventories that must be accounted for in different ways; raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Any wages paid to workers or a group of workers which may directly co-relate to any specific activity of production, maintenance, transportation of material, or product, and directly associate in the conversion of raw material into finished goods are called **direct labour**.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Wages paid to trainees or apprentices does not come under the category of direct labour as they have no significant value.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] These categories are flexible, sometimes overlapping as different cost accounting principles are applied.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] By function: production, administration, selling and distribution, or research and development.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] By behavior: fixed, variable, or semi-variable.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Fixed costs remain unchanged irrespective of changes in the production volume over a given period of time.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Variable costs change according to the volume of production.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Semi-variable costs are partly fixed and partly variable.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] By controllability: Controllable costs are those which can be controlled or influenced by conscious management action.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Uncontrollable costs cannot be controlled or influenced by conscious management action.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] By normality: normal costs and abnormal costs.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Normal costs arise during routine day-to-day business operations.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Abnormal costs arise because of any abnormal activity or event not part of routine business operations, such as accidents or natural disasters.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] By time: Historical costs and predetermined costs.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Historical costs are costs incurred in the past.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Predetermined costs are computed in advance on basis of factors affecting cost elements.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Differential costs: This cost is the difference in total cost resulting from selecting one alternative over another.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Opportunity costs: The value of a benefit sacrificed in favour of an alternative course of action.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Relevant cost: The relevant cost is a cost which is relevant in various decisions of management.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Replacement cost: This cost is the cost at which existing items of material or fixed assets can be replaced at present or at a future date.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Shutdown cost: Costs incurred if operations are shut down, and which would not occur if operations are continued.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Capacity cost: The cost incurred by a company for providing production, administration and selling and distribution capabilities in order to perform various functions.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Sunk cost: A cost already incurred, which cannot be recovered.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Standard Costing is a technique of Cost Accounting to compare the actual costs with standard costs (that are pre-defined) with the help of Variance Analysis.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] It is used to understand the variations of product costs in manufacturing.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Standard costing allocates fixed costs incurred in an accounting period to the goods produced during that period.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] It also essentially enabled managers to ignore the fixed costs, and look at the results of each period in relation to the "standard cost" for any given product.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For Example: if the railway coach company normally produced 40 coaches per month, and the fixed costs were still $1000/month, then each coach could be said to incur an Operating Cost/overhead of $25 =($1000 / 40).
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Adding this to the variable costs of $300 per coach produced a full cost of $325 per coach.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] This method tended to slightly distort the resulting unit cost, but in mass-production industries that made one product line, and where the fixed costs were relatively low, the distortion was very minor.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For Example: if the railway coach company made 100 coaches one month, then the unit cost would become $310 per coach ($300 + ($1000 / 100)).
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] If the next month the company made 50 coaches, then the unit cost = $320 per coach ($300 + ($1000 / 50)), a relatively minor difference.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] As business became more complex and began producing a greater variety of products, the use of cost accounting to make decisions to maximize profitability came into question.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Management circles became increasingly aware of the theory of constraints in the 1980s and began to understand that "every production process has a limiting factor" somewhere in the chain of production.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] As business management learned to identify the constraints, they increasingly adopted throughput accounting to manage them and "maximize the *throughput dollars*" (or other currency) from each unit of constrained resource.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Throughput accounting aims to make the best use of scarce resources (bottleneck) in a JIT (Just in time) environment.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] "Throughput", in this context, refers to the amount of money obtained from sales minus the cost of materials that have gone into making them.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Activity-based costing (ABC) is a system for assigning costs to products based on the activities they require.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] In this case, activities are those regular actions performed inside a company.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] "Talking with the customer regarding invoice questions" is an example of activity inside most companies.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Companies may be moved to adopt ABC by a need to improve costing accuracy, that is, understand better the true costs and profitability of individual products, services, or initiatives.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] ABC gets closer to true costs in these areas by turning many costs that standard cost accounting views as indirect costs essentially into direct costs.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] By contrast, standard cost accounting typically determines so-called indirect and overhead costs simply as a percentage of certain direct costs, which may or may not reflect actual resource usage for individual items.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Under ABC, accountants assign 100% of each employee's time to the different activities performed inside a company (many will use surveys to have the workers themselves assign their time to the different activities).
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The accountant then can determine the total cost spent on each activity by summing up the percentage of each worker's salary spent on that activity.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] A company can use the resulting activity cost data to determine where to focus its operational improvements.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example, a job-based manufacturer may find that a high percentage of its workers are spending their time trying to figure out a hastily written customer order.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Via (ABC) Activity-based costing, the accountants now have a currency amount pegged to the activity of "Researching Customer Work Order Specifications".
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Senior management can now decide how much focus or money to budget for resolving this process deficiency.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Activity-based management includes (but is not restricted to) the use of activity-based costing to manage a business.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] While (ABC) Activity-based costing may be able to pinpoint the cost of each activity and resources into the ultimate product, the process could be tedious, costly and subject to errors.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] As it is a tool for a more accurate way of allocating fixed costs into a product, these fixed costs do not vary according to each month's production volume.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example, the elimination of one product would not eliminate the overhead or even direct labour cost assigned to it.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Activity-based costing (ABC) better identifies product costing in the long run, but may not be too helpful in day-to-day decision-making.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Recently, Mocciaro Li Destri, Picone and Minà (2012) proposed a performance and cost measurement system that integrates the Economic Value Added criteria with Process-Based Costing (PBC).
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The EVA-PBC methodology allows us to implement the EVA management logic not only at the firm level, but also at lower levels of the organization.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] EVA-PBC methodology plays an interesting role in bringing strategy back into financial performance measures.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Lean accounting has developed in recent years to provide the accounting, control, and measurement methods supporting lean manufacturing and other applications of lean thinking such as healthcare, construction, insurance, banking, education, government and other industries.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] There are two main thrusts for Lean Accounting.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The first is the application of lean methods to the company's accounting, control, and measurement processes.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] This is not different from applying lean methods to any other processes.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The objective is to eliminate waste, free up capacity, speed up the process, eliminate errors & defects, and make the process clear and understandable.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Lean Accounting does not require the traditional management accounting methods like standard costing, activity-based costing, variance reporting, cost-plus pricing, complex transactional control systems, and untimely and confusing financial reports.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The cost-volume-profit analysis is the systematic examination of the relationship between selling prices, sales, production volumes, costs, expenses and profits.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] This analysis provides very useful information for decision-making in the management of a company.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example, the analysis can be used in establishing sales prices, in the product mix selection to sell, in the decision to choose marketing strategies, and in the analysis of the impact on profits by changes in costs.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] In the current environment of business, a business administration must act and take decisions in a fast and accurate manner.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] As a result, the importance of cost-volume-profit is still increasing as time passes.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] A relationship between the cost, volume and profit is the contribution margin.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The contribution margin is the revenue excess from sales over variable costs.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The concept of contribution margin is particularly useful in the planning of business because it gives an insight into the potential profits that a business can generate.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The contribution margin can also be expressed as a percentage.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The contribution margin ratio, which is sometimes called the profit-volume ratio, indicates the percentage of each sales dollar available to cover fixed costs and to provide operating revenue.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The contribution margin ratio measures the effect on operating income of an increase or a decrease in sales volume.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] For example, assume that the management of Fusion, Inc. is studying the effect of adding $80,000 in sales orders.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Multiplying the contribution margin ratio (40%) by the change in sales volume ($80,000) indicates that operating income will increase $32,000 if additional orders are obtained.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Variable costs as a percentage of sales are equal to 100% minus the contribution margin ratio.
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] The total contribution margin $432,000, can also be computed directly by multiplying the sales by the contribution margin ratio ($1,080,000 X 40%).
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Relevant cost data or pricing data may be required from the supplier, in order to undertake a "cost realism analysis", also known as a "price realism analysis".
[src:finops-practices/cost-accounting] Similarly, where a government agency requests a fixed price submission, provision may be made for a cost or price realism analysis to take place during the evaluation process.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] In **management accounting** or **managerial accounting**, managers use accounting information in decision-making and to assist in the management and performance of their control functions.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] One simple definition of management accounting is the provision of financial and non-financial decision-making information to managers.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] In other words, management accounting helps the directors inside an organization to make decisions.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] This is the way toward distinguishing, examining, deciphering and imparting data to supervisors to help accomplish business goals.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The information gathered includes all fields of accounting that educates the administration regarding business tasks identifying with the financial expenses and decisions made by the organization.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Accountants use plans to measure the overall strategy of operations within the organization.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Management accountants (also called managerial accountants) look at the events that happen in and around a business while considering the needs of the business.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Cost accounting is the process of translating these estimates and data into knowledge that will ultimately be used to guide decision-making.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The Chartered Institute of Management Accountants (CIMA) being the largest management accounting institute with over 100,000 members describes Management accounting as analysing information to advise business strategy and drive sustainable business success.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The Institute of Certified Management Accountants (ICMA) has over 15,000 qualified professionals worldwide, with members in 50-countries.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Its CMA postgraduate education program now is firmly established in 19 overseas markets, namely Bangladesh, Cambodia, China, Cyprus, Dubai, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia, Iran, Japan, Lebanon, Malaysia, Nepal, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, Philippines; Singapore, Sri Lanka, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] To facilitate its educational objectives, the Institute has accredited a number of universities whose master's degree subjects are equivalent to the CMA program.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Some of these universities also provide in-house training and examinations for the CMA program.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Accounting graduates can complete CMA-accredited units at these universities to qualify for CMA status.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The ICMA also has a number of Recognised Provider Institutions (RPIs) that run the CMA program in Australia and overseas.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The CMA program is also available online in regions where face-to-face delivery of the program is not possible.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Management accountants are seen as the "value-creators" amongst the accountants.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] They are more concerned with forward-looking and taking decisions that will affect the future of the organization; than in the historical recording and compliance (score keeping) aspects of the profession.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Management accounting knowledge and experience can be obtained from varied fields and functions within an organization, such as information management, treasury, efficiency auditing, marketing, valuation, pricing, and logistics.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] In 2014 CIMA created the Global Management Accounting Principles (GMAPs).
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The result of research from across 20 countries in five continents, the principles aim to guide best practice in the discipline.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The distinction between **traditional** and **innovative** accounting practices is illustrated with the visual timeline *(see sidebar)* of managerial costing approaches presented at the Institute of Management Accountants 2011 Annual Conference.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Traditional standard costing must comply with generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP US) and actually aligns itself more with answering financial accounting requirements rather than providing solutions for management accountants.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Traditional approaches limit themselves by defining cost behavior only in terms of production or sales volume.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] In the late 1980s, accounting practitioners and educators were heavily criticized on the grounds that management accounting practices (and, even more so, the curriculum taught to accounting students) had changed little over the preceding 60 years, despite radical changes in the business environment.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] In 1993, the Accounting Education Change Commission Statement Number 4 calls for faculty members to expand their knowledge about the actual practice of accounting in the workplace.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Professional accounting institutes, perhaps fearing that management accountants would increasingly be seen as superfluous in business organizations, subsequently devoted considerable resources to the development of a more innovative skills set for management accountants.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Variance analysis is a systematic approach to the comparison of the actual and budgeted costs of the raw materials and labour used during a production period.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] While some form of variance analysis is still used by most manufacturing firms, it nowadays tends to be used in conjunction with innovative techniques such as *life cycle cost analysis* and *activity-based costing*, which are designed with specific aspects of the modern business environment in mind.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Both lifecycle costing and activity-based costing recognize that, in the typical modern factory, the avoidance of disruptive events (such as machine breakdowns and quality control failures) is of far greater importance than (for example) reducing the costs of raw materials.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Activity-based costing also de-emphasizes direct labor as a cost driver and concentrates instead on activities that drive costs, as the provision of a service or the production of a product component.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Other approach is the German Grenzplankostenrechnung (GPK) costing methodology.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Although it has been in practiced in Europe for more than 50 years, neither GPK nor the proper treatment of 'unused capacity' is widely practiced in the U.S.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Another accounting practice available today is resource consumption accounting (RCA).
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] RCA has been recognized by the International Federation of Accountants (IFAC) as a "sophisticated approach at the upper levels of the continuum of costing techniques".
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The approach provides the ability to derive costs directly from operational resource data or to isolate and measure unused capacity costs.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] RCA was derived by taking costing characteristics of GPK, and combining the use of activity-based drivers when needed, such as those used in activity-based costing.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] A modern approach to close accounting is continuous accounting, which focuses on achieving a point-in-time close, where accounting processes that are typically performed at period-end are distributed evenly throughout the period.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Consistent with other roles in modern corporations, management accountants have a dual reporting relationship.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The activities management accountants provide inclusive of forecasting and planning, performing variance analysis, reviewing and monitoring costs inherent in the business are ones that have dual accountability to both finance and the business team.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Examples of tasks where accountability may be more meaningful to the business management team vs. the corporate finance department are the development of new product costing, operations research, business driver metrics, sales management scorecarding, and client profitability analysis.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] A function of management accounting in such organizations is to work closely with the IT department to provide IT cost transparency.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Given the above, one view of the progression of the accounting and finance career path is that financial accounting is a stepping stone to management accounting.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Consistent with the notion of value creation, management accountants help drive the success of the business while strict financial accounting is more of a compliance and historical endeavor.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Activity-based costing was first clearly defined in 1987 by Robert S.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Bruns as a chapter in their book *Accounting and Management: A Field Study Perspective*.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] They initially focused on the manufacturing industry, where increasing technology and productivity improvements have reduced the relative proportion of the direct costs of labor and materials, but have increased relative proportion of indirect costs.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] For example, increased automation has reduced labor, which is a direct cost, but has increased depreciation, which is an indirect cost.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Grenzplankostenrechnung (GPK) is a German costing methodology, developed in the late 1940s and 1960s, designed to provide a consistent and accurate application of how managerial costs are calculated and assigned to a product or service.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The term Grenzplankostenrechnung, often referred to as GPK, has best been translated as either *marginal planned cost accounting* or *flexible analytic cost planning and accounting*.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The origins of GPK are credited to Hans Georg Plaut, an automotive engineer, and Wolfgang Kilger, an academic, working towards the mutual goal of identifying and delivering a sustained methodology designed to correct and enhance cost accounting information.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] GPK is published in cost accounting textbooks, notably *Flexible Plankostenrechnung und Deckungsbeitragsrechnung* and taught at German-speaking universities.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] In the mid- to late-1990s several books were written about accounting in the lean enterprise (companies implementing elements of the Toyota Production System).
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The term *lean accounting* was coined during that period.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] These books contest that traditional accounting methods are better suited for mass production and do not support or measure good business practices in just-in-time manufacturing and services.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The movement reached a tipping point during the 2005 Lean Accounting Summit in Dearborn, Michigan, United States.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] 320 individuals attended and discussed the advantages of a new approach to accounting in the lean enterprise.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] 520 individuals attended the 2nd annual conference in 2006 and it has varied between 250 and 600 attendees since that time.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Resource consumption accounting (RCA) is formally defined as a dynamic, fully integrated, principle-based, and comprehensive management accounting approach that provides managers with decision support information for enterprise optimization.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] RCA emerged as a management accounting approach around 2000 and was subsequently developed at CAM-I, the Consortium for Advanced Manufacturing–International, in a Cost Management Section *RCA interest group* in December 2001.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The most significant recent direction in managerial accounting is throughput accounting; which recognizes the interdependencies of modern production processes.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] For any given product, customer or supplier, it is a tool to measure the contribution per unit of constrained resource.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Management accounting is an applied discipline used in various industries.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The specific functions and principles followed can vary based on the industry.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Management accounting principles in banking are specialized but do have some common fundamental concepts used whether the industry is manufacturing-based or service-oriented.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] For example, transfer pricing is a concept used in manufacturing but is also applied in banking.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] It is a fundamental principle used in assigning value and revenue attribution to the various business units.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Essentially, transfer pricing in banking is the method of assigning the interest rate risk of the bank to the various funding sources and uses of the enterprise.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Thus, the bank's corporate treasury department will assign funding charges to the business units for their use of the bank's resources when they make loans to clients.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The treasury department will also assign funding credit to business units who bring in deposits (resources) to the bank.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Although the funds transfer pricing process is primarily applicable to the loans and deposits of the various banking units, this proactive is applied to all assets and liabilities of the business segment.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] There are a variety of ways to keep current and continue to build one's knowledge base in the field of management accounting.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Certified Management Accountants (CMAs) are required to achieve continuing education hours every year, similar to a Certified Public Accountant.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] A company may also have research and training materials available for use in a corporate owned library.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] This is more common in Fortune 500 companies who have the resources to fund this type of training medium.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] There are also journals, online articles and blogs available.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The journal *Cost Management* (ISSN 1092-8057) and the Institute of Management Accounting (IMA) site are sources which include *Management Accounting Quarterly* and *Strategic Finance* publications.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] Listed below are the primary tasks/services performed by management accountants.
[src:finops-practices/management-accounting] The degree of complexity relative to these activities are dependent on the experience level and abilities of any one individual.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] For manufacturing, as TCO is typically compared with doing business overseas, it goes beyond the initial manufacturing cycle time and cost to make parts.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO includes a variety of cost of doing business items, for example, ship and re-ship, and opportunity costs, while it also considers incentives developed for an alternative approach.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Incentives and other variables include tax credits, common language, expedited delivery, and customer-oriented supplier visits.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO, when incorporated into a financial benefit analysis, provides a cost basis for determining the total economic value of an investment.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include: return on investment, internal rate of return, economic value added, return on information technology, and rapid economic justification.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] The roots of this concept date at least back to the first quarter of the twentieth century.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Many different methodologies and software tools have been developed to analyze TCO in various operational contexts.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis includes total cost of acquisition and operating costs, as well as costs related to replacement or upgrades at the end of the life cycle.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis is used to gauge the viability of any capital investment.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] An enterprise may use it as a product/process comparison tool.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] It is also used by credit markets and financing agencies.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO directly relates to an enterprise's asset and/or related systems total costs across all projects and processes, thus giving a picture of the profitability over time.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO analysis was popularized by the Gartner Group in 1987.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO is applied to the analysis of information technology products, seeking to quantify the financial impact of deploying a product over its life cycle.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] These technologies include software and hardware, and training.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] In the case of comparing TCO of existing versus proposed solutions, consideration should be put toward costs required to maintain the existing solution that may not necessarily be required for a proposed solution.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include cost of manual processing that are only required to support lack of existing automation, and extended support personnel.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Total cost of ownership can be applied to the structure and systems of a single building or a campus of buildings.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Pioneered by Doug Christensen and the facilities department at Brigham Young University starting in the 1980s, the concept gained more traction in educational facilities in the early 21st century.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] A key objective of planning, constructing, operating, and managing buildings via TCO principals is for building owners and facility professionals to predict needs and deliver data-driven results.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO can be applied any time during the life of a facility asset to manage cost inputs for the life of the structure or system into the future.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA, an ANSI Accredited Standards Developer, published *APPA 1000-1 – Total Cost of Ownership for Facilities Asset Management (TCO) – Part 1: Key Principles* as an American National Standard in December 2017.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-1 provides financial officers, facility professionals, architects, planners, construction workforce, and operations and maintenance (O&M) personnel the foundation of a standardized and holistic approach to implementing TCO key principles.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Implementation of TCO key principles can improve decision making, maximizing financial strategies over the life of an asset, starting at the planning and design stage and extends to the end of the asset's life.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-2, slated for publication in 2019, will focus on implementation and application of key TCO principals in facility management.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] The TCO concept is easily applicable to the transportation industry and to motor vehicle ownership, for example, the TCO defines the cost of owning an automobile from the time of purchase by the owner, through its operation and maintenance to the time it leaves the possession of the owner.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Comparative TCO studies between various models help consumers choose a car to fit their needs and budget.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] For personal vehicles in the United States, AAA's annual *Your Driving Costs* study estimated the average total cost of new-vehicle ownership at $11,577 per year in 2025, driven by depreciation, financing, fuel, insurance, maintenance, and license fees.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] In the truck industry, TCO is an essential factor for truck fleet managers.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] By calculating the Total Cost of Ownership of a truck, the truck manager obtains a price per kilometer that varies according to fuel costs, the purchase price, and the resale price of the truck.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] If the truck is financed, the TCO also varies according to the interest rate on the loan.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] These factors in the trucking industry allow managers to make a clearer choice about which truck to select for their truck fleet, because when a transportation company wants to acquire 1 to 10 trucks, TCO is an essential factor to consider for the company's cash flow.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO does not assess how well a solution offers value for money, or how well it fits with an organisation's strategic objectives.
[src:finops-practices/total-cost-of-ownership] Some TCO analyses may include social and environmental costs but this is not always the case.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] FinOps is a cultural practice at its core.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] It’s the way for teams to manage and optimize technology value, where everyone takes ownership of their cost and usage supported by a central best-practices group.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Cross-functional teams in Engineering, Finance, Product, etc. work together to enable faster product delivery, while at the same time gaining more financial control and predictability, enabling stronger Executive decision making.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Other names for the practice include “Cloud Financial Management”, “Cloud Financial Engineering” “Cloud Cost Management”, “Cloud Optimization”, or “Cloud Financial Optimization”.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Regardless of the name, FinOps is the practice of bringing a financial accountability cultural change to how technology value is measured across categories like Cloud, SaaS, PaaS, Licensing, Data Centers, Data Cloud Platforms, and more.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] It enables distributed engineering and business teams to make trade-offs between speed, cost, and quality in their architecture and investment decisions.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Strategic technology investments can drive more revenue, signal customer base growth, enable more product and feature release velocity, or even refine and streamline the entire IT estate.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] FinOps is all about removing blockers against these valuable initiatives; empowering engineering teams to deliver better features, apps, and migrations faster; and enabling a cross-functional conversation about where to invest and when into a variety of technologies.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Sometimes a business will decide to tighten the belt; sometimes it’ll decide to invest more.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] But now teams know which of their technology investments return the most value and can make better, confident decisions into the future.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] The FinOps Foundation offers a variety of ways to learn about the discipline, depending on your familiarity and time commitment.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] **Attend an upcoming FinOps Event:** Meet and learn from like-minded practitioners and experts in welcoming, inclusive environments (both regional and virtual) designed to connect people and inspire new ideas.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Supplement your self-paced learning by familiarizing yourself with the FinOps Framework, and check out FinOps Assets from our Working Groups, including Papers and Playbooks to help inform, empower, and expand your practice.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Check out our monthly Virtual Summits and practitioner presentations and our FinOps X Session Library to catch up on a variety of FinOps Capabilities and Topics, and see how other global practitioners are advancing their practice.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Check out our Adopting FinOps asset that includes step-by-step descriptions on how to get started, as well as **Intro to FinOps slides** in Google Slides or Powerpoint.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Benchmark and compare your organization’s progress against our annual industry snapshot, the State of FinOps.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] FinOps Principles create financial accountability through collaboration and drive business value for technology spend.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] While a central FinOps function may work to enable organizational change, FinOps is not done by a single person or team but rather changes the way that disparate engineering, finance, and business teams work together.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Individuals at every level and in every area of an organization can have a different role to play in the FinOps practice: Executives, Engineers, FinOps Practitioners, Operations, Finance and Procurement.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Read more about FinOps Personas and Roles.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] The practice of FinOps is inherently iterative and maturity of any given process, functional activity, Capability or Domain will improve with repetition.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Typically a “Crawl” stage organization is highly reactive and focused on addressing problems after they occur, while a Run stage practice is proactively factoring cost into their architecture design choices and ongoing engineering processes.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] A “Crawl, Walk, Run” maturity approach to performing FinOps enables organizations to start small, and grow in scale, scope and complexity as business value warrants maturing a functional activity.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Taking quick action at a small scale and limited scope allows FinOps teams to assess the outcomes of their actions, and to gain insights into the value of taking further action in a larger, faster, or more granular way.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Learn more about FinOps Maturity in the FinOps Framework.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] FinOps Scopes establish the decision context and a shared reference to align stakeholders, activities, and outcomes within a FinOps practice.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] This context enables the development of practice profiles that determine which Personas are engaged, which Capabilities are applied, and which Domains define success.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] The FinOps Foundation supports the development of an open-source technical specification for technology billing data.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] The FinOps Open Cost and Usage Specification (FOCUS™), defines a unified format for data providers to produce consistent billing datasets.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] FOCUS enables FinOps Practitioners to more easily unlock data-driven decision-making and maximize the business value of their technologies, while making their skills more transferable across clouds, tools, and organizations.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] The largest cloud service providers – **Microsoft Azure**, **Google Cloud**, **Oracle Cloud** Infrastructure (OCI), and Amazon Web Services (**AWS**) – all offer FOCUS-formatted cost and usage billing data exports directly from their native consoles.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] SaaS providers, like Databricks, Grafana, and more, join in this effort to unify how consumption-based billing data is exported and analyzed by FinOps practitioners.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] Several FinOps tooling vendors also support FOCUS data and generate reports using FOCUS attributes and metrics.
[src:finops-practices/what-is-finops] FinOps Practitioners can learn more about how to obtain FOCUS data from their data generators.
